resent participle: ' (pl. ') \"hearing\"\nBULLET::::- Future participle: ' (pl. ') \"going to hear\"\nBULLET::::- Gerundive: ' (pl. ') \"needing to be heard\"\nBULLET::::- Gerund: ' \"of hearing\", ' \"by /for hearing\", \"in order to hear\"\n\nPrincipal parts of verbs in the fourth conjugation generally adhere to the following patterns:\nBULLET::::- perfect has suffix -vī. Verbs which adhere to this pattern are considered to be \"regular\". Examples:\nBULLET::::- \"to hear, listen (to)\"\nBULLET::::- \"to guard\"\nBULLET::::- \"to sleep\"\nBULLET::::- \"to hinder, impede\"\nBULLET::::- \"to fortify, to build\"\nBULLET::::- \"to punish\"\nBULLET::::- \"to know\"\n\nBULLET::::- perfect has suffix -uī. Examples:\nBULLET::::- \"to open, to uncover\"\n\nBULLET::::- perfect has suffix -sī (-xī when c comes at the end of the root). Examples:\nBULLET::::- \"to surround, to enclose\"\nBULLET::::- \"to confirm, to ratify\"\nBULLET::::- \"to feel, to perceive\"\nBULLET::::- \"to bind\"\n\nBULLET::::- perfect has suffix -ī and reduplication. Examples:\nBULLET::::- \"to find, discover\"\n\nBULLET::::- perfect has suffix -ī and vowel lengthening in the stem. Examples:\nBULLET::::- \"to come, to arrive\"\nBULLET::::- \"to find\"\n\nDeponent verbs in the 4th conjugation include the following:\n\nThe verb \"to arise\" is also regarded as 4th conjugation, although some parts, such as the 3rd singular present tense and imperfect subjunctive , have a short vowel like the 3rd conjugation. But its compound \"to rise up, attack\" is entirely 4th conjugation.\n\nIn the perfect tenses, shortened forms without \"-v-\" are common, for example, for . Cicero, however, prefers the full forms to .\n\nThe verb \"to be\" is the most common verb in Latin. It is conjugated as follows:\n\n!\n!colspan=\"3\"Indicative\n!colspan=\"2\"Subjunctive\n!\nPresentFutureImperfectPresentImperfect\n!rowspan=2Active\n\"I am\"\"I will be\"\"I was\"  \"I may be\"\"I might be\"\n\"Iyou sg.he, she, itweyou pl.they\"\n